\par This is similar to Step 2 of the seven-step algorithm - except we relax our goals. Instead of requiring that all edges are oriented correctly, we require only that a low edge and its corresponding hi
gh edge be oriented the same way: both correctly or both incorrectly. If they are not oriented the same way, then we cannot match them up in steps 3 and 4. We will later orient the edge pairs correctly in Step 5.
\par In this step, we want the number of flipped edges to be a multiple of 4 so that the number of flipped edge pairs is even. This will take care of the orientation parity problem. We also want to match the permutation parities of the low and high edges.
